Here's a clean approach using merged `ResourceDictionary` files:

**1. Define theme dictionaries** (e.g., `Themes/LightTheme.xaml`, `DarkTheme.xaml`, `HighContrastTheme.xaml`):

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**2. Create a `ThemeService`** to swap dictionaries at runtime:

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always last added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d.Source?.OriginalString.Contains("Theme") == true);
        if (existing != null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        var theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark" => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(theme);

        // Persist choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

**3. Load the saved theme at startup** in `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

**4. Bind UI elements** using `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so they update live:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello!" />
</ContentPage>
```

**5. Settings page picker:**

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string theme)
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

**Key points:**

- Use `DynamicResource` everywhere — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes.
- Keep the same `x:Key` names across all three theme files so lookups resolve correctly.
- `Preferences` persists the choice across app restarts.
- You can also define `Style` objects in each theme dictionary for buttons, entries, etc.
